  "prompt": "How can I stop Outlook from synchronising folders automatically?",
  "response": "If you'd like to stop Outlook from synchronizing folders automatically, you can make adjustments within your account settings. Here are the steps you can follow to achieve this:\n\n### For Outlook Desktop Application:\n1. **Turn Off Cached Exchange Mode (For Exchange Accounts):**\n   - Open Outlook.\n   - Click on `File`.\n   - Select `Account Settings`, then again `Account Settings`.\n   - Choose your email account and click on `Change`.\n   - Uncheck `Use Cached Exchange Mode`.\n   - Click `Next`, then `Finish`, and restart Outlook.\n   \n2. **Adjust Send/Receive Settings (For All Accounts):**\n   - Open Outlook.\n   - Go to the `File` tab.\n   - Select `Options`.\n   - In the navigation pane, click `Advanced`.\n   - Under `Send and receive`, click on `Send/Receive...`.\n   - Select your account in the `Group Name` box (often it is named `All Accounts`).\n   - Uncheck `Schedule an automatic send/receive every X minutes`.\n   - Click `Close`, then `OK`.\n\n### For Outlook on the Web (OWA):\nOutlook on the web doesn't provide direct options to stop synchronizing folders automatically similarly to the desktop application. However, you can manage folders and settings to reduce automatic synchronization.\n\n### Additional Methods:\n- **Disable Automatic Updates:**\n   - Go to `File > Options > Advanced`.\n   - Under `Update`, uncheck all options or ensure synchronization settings that could be pushing automatic updates are disabled.\n\n- **Manual Send/Receive:**\n   - You can also manually control send/receive actions:\n     - Click on the `Send/Receive` tab.\n     - Select options like `Send/Receive All Folders`.\n\nThese steps should help you gain more control over how Outlook synchronizes folders, reducing its automatic syncing activities.\n\nDo note that stopping synchronization may impact receiving new emails automatically and other syncing features like calendar updates.",
